The wading wood copies the frames of the windows, the beams, the decorations of the doors, the mirrors and the letters.
The Casa Batlló, located in the Eixample neighborhood in the 43rd of the lively commercial street of Passeig de Gràcia, emerged from the remodeling of a house in 1877 by architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction lasted two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the industrial rich Josep Batlló, initially insisted on overthrowing the previous building and starting at zero, but soon accepted Gaudí's idea of a new and cheaper reconstruction.
However, the Batlló House, consisting of several apartments, did not design it alone, Antoni Gaudí.
