Because of its organic form, the locals soon after its completion captured "the house of the bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows, began to call it "the house of the trash".
It is also said that, at the height of the construction, the sword of San Jorge, patron of Catalonia appears.
Other sculptural elements of the building hide religious motives.
Gaudí designed a unique system at home for the central heating era with ventilating respirators and typical fireplaces.
It may be strange to have its slope of forty-five degrees.
During the construction, Gaudí did not comply at all with the construction standards of the moment and was not influenced by them.
However, the construction was granted a permit from the beginning, although it clearly showed that the planned reconstruction data were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the town was so affected by the result that it was requested to be corrected.
For example, he was upset that the construction included columns even to the public steel.
The arrangements were never made, rather the contrary: only 15 days after the city's request, Joseph Batlló requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two tallest floors of the building.
The owner himself was installed on the lower floors.
In the gallery of the second floor there was the living room and in the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The house, of six floors, is completely crossed by a staircase that leads to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform were to break all right angles and lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the halls and a larger group can be communicated in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy required for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaudí, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaudí plays with light, white blues and blues that cover the inner courtyard and tragaluces.
The game with the two colors brings the maximum light on all the floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which on the contrary absorb sunlight.
Anyone can visit the Batlló House, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and recharged apartment available to the public.
