More and more parents use tracking devices to control their children
Fear of children leads more and more people to think about controlling them by GPS.
The system, originally designed to track vehicles, can also follow the movement of people and thus contribute, for example, in the event of the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device currently has the approximate size of a lock box, but it will soon be reduced to the size of a clock.
Many people were afraid of the missing Anička and began to inform themselves about the means available to protect their children better.
Even at the cost of attacking your privacy.
"We all try to say that it is not about spying, but about another way to reduce the possibility of a tragedy," says Petr Pilin of Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices in the Czech market.
"I recognize that, in certain cases, such devices can be abused, for example if they are put in someone's pocket without their knowledge, but we have not yet met with such cases."
"Most customers really buy it for security reasons," Pilin adds.
In their view, children should always know what the "cajita" is for and how it is used in case of emergency.
Child psychologist Dana Bočkova warns about the fact that if the child does not want to take it, he will just pull it off.
"Even younger children show great creativity when they deliberately lose certain things if they want to avoid controlling them."
"Before, the parents had enormous confidence in the mobiles, but these could be shut down as easily as the tracking device," Bočkova says.
In his view, it is questionable whether such a device is really useful in the event of an attack.
"If this is a prepared kidnapping, the author will practically always check that the child carries some kind of electronic device that can reveal his location."
"Now it's the phone."
"As the use of tracking devices is expanding, you will also search for them, as your sale will undoubtedly be made with much publicity."
"In such cases, criminals always go a step ahead of the police," says the psychologist.
However, it adds that such devices can help in the case of an improvised attack of a pedophile.
According to Robert Čech of the RC Monitoring company, which provides tracking services for both vehicles and people, even if, after an attack, the tracking device is destroyed immediately, its presence can be helpful.
"The device can be configured to send the position regularly after a certain period."
"If damage occurs, at least it will facilitate the last position of the person concerned."
"The most expensive devices are integrated with a tilt meter, so if the person just wakes up and remains mobile, the device will immediately issue a warning with the position in question," says Čech.
