Support for democracy in Latin America continues to increase, as well as support for private enterprises.
Crime is more worrying than unemployment.
In addition, in most of the region, Brazil is seen as a more influential country than the United States.
These are some of the conclusions of the latest Latinobarometer survey conducted in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Since the survey has been conducted regularly since 1995, it is possible to monitor changes in attitudes in the region.
The results of this year's survey, conducted in September and early October, highlight two related issues.
The first is the relatively animated humor ruling in Latin America.
The second is the growing stability of attitudes towards democracy and its main institutions.
Support for democracy has increased considerably in several countries on the coast of the Pacific of South America (see table 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has reached an average of 6 per cent annually since 2002, support for democracy has increased from 40% in 2005 to 61 per cent this year.
He also grew up in Mexico, where the economy has recovered after suffering a great decline in production last year.
However, only half of Mexico and Brazil surveyed, the two most populous countries in the area, are convinced democracies, which lowers the regional average (see chart 2).
About 44 per cent of the surveyed in the region were satisfied with the way democracy operates in practice in their country, the same figure as last year, but considerably higher than 25 per cent recorded in 2001 (Graph 3).
About 34 per cent said they trusted the Congress of their country and 45 per cent in their Government, the same amount as last year in both cases, but considerably higher in 2003 (17 per cent and 24 per cent respectively).
A decade ago, economic turmoil in Latin America seriously affected support for democracy.
The fact that it was maintained during the global financial crisis was likely due to the fact that many Latin American countries were only affected by a brief recession and enjoyed a strong recovery.
Moreover, the existence of a stronger social security network has helped to protect the poorest.
(The United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Latin Americans living in poverty is only marginally increased in 2009 and has been reduced again this year to 32 per cent.)
However, the mood varies considerably from country to country (see Graph 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of its outgoing president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is reflected in a general sense of progress.
This feeling is less common in Mexico and Central America, where recession was more serious and has increased violent crimes.
For the second time since the beginning of the surveys, the most surveyed in Latin America mention crime, rather than unemployment, as the most serious problem facing their country (see chart 5).
About 31 per cent claim that, whether they or a close relative, they have been victims of crime in the past year, a figure that has been reduced since 38 per cent last year and that is the lowest recorded percentage since 1995.
The most positive economic performance is reflected in greater support for private enterprises and the market economy: around 71 per cent of the region's respondents claim that private enterprises are essential for development, while in 2007 only 56 per cent (see Graph 6).
About 58% agree that the market economy is the only system that will allow its country to develop, compared with 47% last year.
It is interesting that 62% of Venezuelan respondents feel the same (and 80% support for private companies), although their left-wing president, Hugo Chávez, is expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the country that exercises greater leadership in the region, as indicated by 19 per cent of respondents (18 per cent last year), followed by the United States (9 per cent, the same figure as last year) and Venezuela (9 per cent compared to 11 per cent a year ago).
However, the United States is the country most affected by the surveys in Mexico and most of Central America, while Venezuela bears such a title in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
