For a long time it has been considered that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulphur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria found in Mono Lake, California, can continue to grow after replacing phosphorus by arsenic.
"It makes you wonder what it is possible," said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, finding is important for searching for life on different planets on Earth, as researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know what it has.
