He didn't.
What the discovery "is evidence that in other planetary environments, there might be organisms that use other elements to stimulate their biochemistry and that the set of "standard" elements that we consider essential for life may not be so fixed," commented Charles Cockell, the cathedral of the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, United Kingdom.
Cockell wasn't part of the research team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element by another in basic biochemical and biochemical structure," Cockell added.
The discovery was not by accident.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the NASA Institute of Astrobiology, who conducted the study, focused on the Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one another.
"Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus."
"As a result, it may be difficult for agencies to differentiate them."
"However, arsenic is quite different than so that it does not work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, in some ways, appeals to biochemical machinery," Anbar explains.
Researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to ever-increasing arsenic concentrations, which they managed to adapt and use to grow.
The microbial grows better with phosphorus, but the fact that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that it can naturally exist a form of life that uses arsenic, either in other areas of the Earth or in another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, a professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, pointed out that the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example has never been found that is shown to work.
Arsenic was more common in the early ages of the Earth, he pointed out, so researchers speculated that the early forms of life could have used it.
"So it suggests that there might be other means of generating life, not only the way life was formed in the ancient earth," said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon's research team.
