Yesterday, the United Nations has proposed in Cancún a plan for the renewal of domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in hundreds of countries to reduce greenhouse gas (GEI) to an amount that is practically equivalent to a third of the additional decrease that needs to be carried out to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is reflected in the broad set of major concrete projects that the United Nations expects to be adopted in Cancún to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments in industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, if the incandescent bombs, which still monopolies between 50 and 70% of the market, were replaced by fluo-compact bombs or, better still, by electroluminescent diodes (DEL or "LED" bombs), much of the 1,800 million tonnes (Gt) of GI emitted on the planet would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8 per cent of global emissions.
It is equivalent to 70% of the emissions of the planetary motor park.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans that should reduce GHG global emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, a further 5 Gt of this amount should be reduced to stabilize, before 2020, the rise in temperatures in two centigrades to prevent uncontrolling.
In the incandescent pumps, 95% of the energy is released in the form of heat and the rest, that is, 5%, produces light.
In the case of fluo-compact pumps, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED pumps, energy consumption is reduced twice more.
Fluo-compact pumps last an average of 6,000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bombs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week (a company that has also participated in the UN study), have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bomb, which allows us to make an idea of saving that can be achieved with the replacement plan that would be applied in one hundred countries.
These new bombs can also work with resustants and emit very little heat.
Above all, they don't contain any mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations regarding fluo-compact pumps, since they contain mercury and should be removed as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the manufacturers provide instructions.
However, the report indicates that the main source of mercury emissions on the planet are not the fluo-compact pumps, but the coal thermal power plants, which emit a large amount of mercury to produce the electricity that melts with incandescent bombs.
Only in the United States, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the benefits of this international programme to each country.
For example, Indonesia would thus save billions of dollars a year in electricity and eight million tons of CO2, i.e. the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants whose construction would cost 2,500 million.
