Climate: the French hats in their financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to examine whether the rapidly unblocked (start or early) financing promises made by the developed countries have been respected.
And the French hats have been unveiled.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $3 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union committed itself to providing EUR 7.20 billion in three years and EUR 1.260 million in France (i.e. EUR 420 million per year).
During the opening of COP16, the EU has placed on the table its best letters to convince its partners that its commitment to fast start funding is true: a report detailing the measures of its Member States, a press wheel, a large complementary event, the distribution of brochures...
The transparent operation was appreciated and was appreciated for what it really was: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same and at the same level of precision.
The EU announces that it has released EUR 2,200 million in 2010, which sets it in the right direction towards meeting its commitment of EUR 7,200 million in 2012.
But if we study the situation in detail, things are more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, money must be "new and additional" to ensure that a complementary effort is made, without prejudice to official development aid.
Unfortunately, no agreement has been reached on what "new and additional" means.
When the European Commission proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, have blocked the procedure.
At present, each person chooses the most appropriate reference.
For example, the European Commission has taken the year 2009 as a reference: international funding is maintained and 150 million is added in three years in terms of fast-start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references with regard to the year or level of official development assistance.
On the contrary, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, no reference is made to the expenditure of previous years or to the total level of official development assistance.
In particular, the total amount of France's aid to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), while it seeks to respect its commitment to "new and additional" funds.
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Once again, there is no norm and each one chooses the calculation method.
Some, like France, consider that each euro lent is equivalent to a given euro.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
Although the use of loans can be justified for certain profitable investments (often, projects related to the reduction of emissions based on more efficient technologies), it is worth presenting a euro that will be recovered as equivalent to a euro that is given... As much, only the cost of the loan for the country that grants the loan should be calculated for its commitments (i.e. the equivalent of a kind of interest).
But France does not find such reasoning useful: "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros); see the EU document to see it for itself.
It is the only country in the Union that uses the loan so often.
Germany uses it in 46 per cent, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia, among others, respect their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the majority of the European Union provides a euro to fulfil its commitment, France only gives 10 cents and considers the effort comparable.
A good trick!
In summary, in its early financing, France makes double abuse: on the one hand, in relation to the actions in time and, on the other, in relation to the real financial effort.
With only EUR 36.1 million spent, it is possible to give the impression that it spends 420 million "news and additionals", as promised.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has been involved in arbitration) could have a double negative impact both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give when they can just lend?) as in the negotiations, as developing countries are not stupid...
The chapter of early financing is a short-term reduction in the overall climate negotiations.
But it could be a grain of more sand in the huge machinery that is the CNUCC.
Let's hope it's not like that.
Whatever the case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First, France could announce a change in its method of calculation for the years 2011 and 2012, with the intention of respecting its commitments and in the same way as the other countries of the European Union.
But, in particular, France could make it possible to move forward the debate on gambling bets on long-term financing (another essential chapter currently under discussion): we will not get rid of the question of the "additional character" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on this issue as it is on others.
We therefore hope that the new Minister for the Environment, Mrs Koscisko-Morizet, will arrive at Cancún next week.
A surprising announcement on France's fast start and its vision of "additional character" and the use of loans would help to improve the level of international confidence needed to move forward in negotiations.
